T1  - Market Timing with Option-Implied Distributions: A Forward-Looking Approach
AU  - Kostakis, Alexandros
AU  - Panigirtzoglou, Nikolaos
AU  - Skiadopoulos, George
Y1  - 2011/05/16
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1110.1346
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1110.1346
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1231
EP  - 1249
VL  - 57
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We address the empirical implementation of the static asset allocation problem by developing a forward-looking approach that uses information from market option prices. To this end, we extract constant maturity S&P 500 implied distributions and transform them to the corresponding risk-adjusted ones. Then we form optimal portfolios consisting of a risky and a risk-free asset and evaluate their out-of-sample performance. We find that the use of risk-adjusted implied distributions times the market and makes the investor better off than if she uses historical returns' distributions to calculate her optimal strategy. The results hold under a number of evaluation metrics and utility functions and carry through even when transaction costs are taken into account. Not surprisingly, the reported market timing ability deteriorated during the recent subprime crisis. An extension of the approach to a dynamic asset allocation setting is also presented. This paper was accepted by Wei Xiong, finance.
AB  - We address the empirical implementation of the static asset allocation problem by developing a forward-looking approach that uses information from market option prices. To this end, we extract constant maturity S&P 500 implied distributions and transform them to the corresponding risk-adjusted ones. Then we form optimal portfolios consisting of a risky and a risk-free asset and evaluate their out-of-sample performance. We find that the use of risk-adjusted implied distributions times the market and makes the investor better off than if she uses historical returns' distributions to calculate her optimal strategy. The results hold under a number of evaluation metrics and utility functions and carry through even when transaction costs are taken into account. Not surprisingly, the reported market timing ability deteriorated during the recent subprime crisis. An extension of the approach to a dynamic asset allocation setting is also presented. This paper was accepted by Wei Xiong, finance.
